== Development in the Edo Period == === Background of Reclamation === On the **first day of the eighth month of** {{ill|Tenshō (era)|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|12=draft|12=draft}} **18 (1590)**, {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft|12=draft}} entered {{ill|Edo Castle|ja|江戸城|12=draft|12=draft}}. At that time, the city of Edo had only about 100 thatched-roof houses. However, by {{ill|Keichō (era)|ja|慶長|12=draft|12=draft}} 14 (1609), according to the account of {{ill|Don Rodrigo|ja|ドン・ロドリゴ|12=draft|12=draft}}, the population had already grown to 150,000. By the {{ill|Kyōhō era|ja|享保|12=draft|12=draft}}, the samurai population reached 500,000–600,000, with another 500,000 merchants and laborers{{Sfn|Tokyo Bay History|p=112-113}}. To meet the growing food demand in Edo, the **Tonegawa Eastward Diversion Project** was carried out, and maritime trade routes were opened for transporting rice from **Dewa Province**. The reclamation of Tsubaki Sea was part of this effort{{refnest|group="Note"|**Kawamura Zuiken**, who established the **East and West Shipping Routes**, was also involved in the reclamation of Tsubaki Sea<ref>[https://www.city.sakata.lg.jp/smph/sangyo/kanko/zuiken_sakata.html 河村瑞賢～西廻り航路を開拓したプロジェクトリーダー] - Sakata City. Retrieved August 24, 2022.</ref>.}}.
=== Reclamation of Tsubaki Sea === The first known reclamation attempt was proposed during the **Genna era (1615–1624)** by **Sugiyama Saburōemon**, a merchant from Edo{{sfn|Heibonsha|1996|pp=44-45}}, but the **Tokugawa shogunate** denied permission{{sfn|Chiba Prefectural Historical Research Foundation|2007|pp=817-820}}. Later, during the **Kanbun era (1661–1673)**, **Shirai Jirōemon** petitioned for reclamation, leading to an on-site inspection by **Ina Tadatsune**, but opposition from local villages relying on the lake for irrigation led to rejection once again{{sfn|Heibonsha|1996|pp=44-45}}{{sfn|Chiba Prefectural Historical Research Foundation|2007|pp=817-820}}.
Further efforts, challenges, and eventual success in reclaiming Tsubaki Sea continued throughout the late **17th century**, eventually forming highly fertile farmland known as **Higata Hachiman-goku**. == See Also == * {{ill|List of lakes and marshes in Japan|ja|日本の湖沼一覧|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Kamatsu Ise Grand Shrine|ja|鎌数伊勢大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}
